urning-rewrite/tests/conformance/features/workspace_init.feature` — Gherkin scenarios for init\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/conformance/features/flow_discovery.feature` — Gherkin scenarios for flow commands\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit/domain_test.rs` — unit tests for domain types\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit/flow_preset_test.rs` — unit tests for flow preset definitions\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit/workspace_test.rs` — unit tests for workspace config serialization\n\n## Dependencies\n- Requires: none (first slice)\n- Blocks: slice 2 (flow preset definitions + stage contracts + renderer contracts), slice 3 (workspace governance effective config), slice 4 (project/run canonical store)\n\n---\n\nFILE /root/new-ralph-burning/.ralph/projects/ralph-burning-rewrite/loops/002-stage-contract-registry-and-deterministic/20260311183324-spec.md\n---\nartifact: spec\nloop: 2\nproject: ralph-burning-rewrite\nbackend: codex(gpt-5.4-xhigh)\nrole: planner\ncreated_at: 2026-03-11T18:33:24Z\n---\n\nI’m reviewing `prompt.md`, the completed loop artifact, and recent git history to determine what’s already in place and what the next missing feature slice should be.\nI have the loop and commit boundaries. Next I’m reading the actual prompt/spec inputs and the rewrite code so I can separate shipped foundation work from the next missing slice.\nThe prompt lives under the existing orchestration workspace, not the rewrite tree. I’m pulling the project prompt plus loop spec and current implementation surface together now.\nThe checked-in crate is still a narrow foundation slice. I’m reading the workflow and workspace modules now to verify whether stage contracts, effective config, or any project/run persistence already slipped in before I plan the next feature.\nI’ve confirmed the current code matches the approved loop-1 foundation plus a later `flake.nix` addition. I’m checking the checkpoint diffs now so the next feature is anchored to what actually changed between planning, implementation, review, and current HEAD.\n# Feature: Stage Contract Registry and Deterministic Artifact Rendering\n\n## Description\nLoop 1 is complete: the approved artifact and git checkpoints `1dbe79b` through `60e6d0c` delivered the Rust crate skeleton, bounded-context module layout, workspace init, built-in flow discovery, and the shared `FlowPreset` / `StageId` foundation. The only later change at `cac0f25` adds `flake.nix` support and does not add workflow behavior. The next missing slice is the unfinished remainder of roadmap step 2: a `StageContract` and renderer layer for the already-defined stages. The current codebase has no stage payload schemas, no semantic validators, no failure-class mapping, and no deterministic Markdown artifact rendering, so later work on agent execution and `run start` would otherwise have no canonical contract to target.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Add a `StageContract` registry keyed by the existing `StageId`, and every stage already present in the four built-in presets resolves to exactly one contract without changing any approved flow IDs or stage ordering.\n- [ ] Introduce typed stage payload models plus JSON Schema generation/validation for all supported stages: `prompt_review`, `planning`, `implementation`, `qa`, `review`, `completion_panel`, `acceptance_qa`, `final_review`, `plan_and_implement`, `apply_fixes`, `docs_plan`, `docs_update`, `docs_validation`, `ci_plan`, `ci_update`, and `ci_validation`.\n- [ ] Planning-style contracts (`prompt_review`, `planning`, `docs_plan`, `ci_plan`) require structured problem framing, assumptions or open questions, ordered proposed work, and explicit readiness or risk fields.\n- [ ] Execution/update contracts (`implementation`, `plan_and_implement`, `apply_fixes`, `docs_update`, `ci_update`) require structured change summaries, intended or completed steps, validation evidence or plans, and outstanding-risk fields.\n- [ ] Validation/review contracts (`qa`, `docs_validation`, `ci_validation`, `acceptance_qa`, `review`, `final_review`, `completion_panel`) require an explicit outcome/decision enum plus evidence, findings or gaps, and follow-up or amendment data when the outcome is not cleanly approved.\n- [ ] Contract evaluation order is fixed: schema validation runs first, semantic validation runs only on schema-valid payloads, and rendering runs only on payloads that passed both prior steps.\n- [ ] Introduce the canonical failure-class enum needed by later slices, including `transport_failure`, `schema_validation_failure`, `domain_validation_failure`, `timeout`, `cancellation`, and `qa_review_outcome_failure`.\n- [ ] Stage contracts map non-passing QA/review/completion decisions to `qa_review_outcome_failure` without treating them as schema or domain failures.\n- [ ] State invariants for this slice are explicit: on schema failure, semantic validation and rendering do not run; on domain failure, rendering does not run; on any failure, no success bundle is returned; callers receive either `validated payload + rendered artifact` together or an error, never one without the other.\n- [ ] Markdown renderers are deterministic and stage-specific: the same validated payload always renders byte-identical output, uses canonical `cycle` terminology, and is derived only from validated structured fields rather than raw backend text.\n- [ ] Raw backend output remains diagnostic-only input to the contract evaluator and is kept separate from payload and artifact outputs so later persistence work can store diagnostics without using Markdown as protocol.\n- [ ] Add unit tests proving every stage in every built-in flow has contract coverage, schema failures short-circuit semantic validation, semantic failures short-circuit rendering, and repeated renders of the same payload are identical.\n- [ ] Add conformance scenario IDs for successful contract evaluation, schema failure, domain failure, and QA/review outcome failure so later `run start` work inherits fixed public expectations.\n- [ ] `cargo test` and `cargo clippy --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings` pass after the contract and renderer modules are added.\n\n## Files to Modify/Create\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/Cargo.toml` - add schema/validation dependencies needed for typed JSON Schema support\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/shared/domain.rs` - add shared failure-class and artifact/contract identity types used across contracts\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/shared/error.rs` - add explicit schema-validation, domain-validation, and renderer error variants\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/workflow_composition/mod.rs` - expose the stage-contract registry alongside the existing flow definitions\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/workflow_composition/contracts.rs` - define `StageContract`, registry lookup, contract evaluation ordering, and failure mapping\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/workflow_composition/payloads.rs` - define typed payload structs and schema metadata for each stage or contract family\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/workflow_composition/renderers.rs` - implement deterministic Markdown renderers from validated payloads\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit.rs` - register new unit test modules\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit/stage_contract_test.rs` - cover registry completeness, validation ordering, and failure-class behavior\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit/renderer_test.rs` - cover deterministic rendering and artifact content shape\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/conformance/features/stage_contracts.feature` - add scenario IDs describing contract success and failure behavior\n\n## Dependencies\n- Requires: Loop 1 foundation — domain model, workspace init, and flow discovery\n- Blocks: agent execution facade with structured-output guarantee, standard preset `run start` vertical path, and later retry/remediation semantics\n\n---\n\nFILE /root/new-ralph-burning/.ralph/projects/ralph-burning-rewrite/loops/003-workspace-governance-effective-config-and-active/20260311191151-spec.md\n---\nartifact: spec\nloop: 3\nproject: ralph-burning-rewrite\nbackend: claude(opus)\nrole: planner\ncreated_at: 2026-03-11T19:11:51Z\n---\n\nNow I have a complete picture of the project state. Let me analyze and produce the next feature spec.\n\n**Completed:**\n- Loop 1 (roadmap slice 1): Foundation — domain model, workspace init, flow discovery\n- Loop 2 (roadmap slice 2): Stage contract registry and deterministic artifact rendering\n\n**Next in roadmap:** Slice 3 — Workspace governance effective config + active project resolution\n\n# Feature: Workspace Governance Effective Config and Active Project Resolution\n\n## Description\nImplement roadmap slice 3: layered workspace configuration with `config show/get/set/edit` CLI commands, and active-project resolution via the `.ralph-burning/active-project` pointer file. The existing `workspace_governance` context currently handles workspace init and config loading but has no support for effective configuration (workspace-level defaults, runtime overrides), mutable config updates, or tracking which project is currently selected. This slice fills that gap so that downstream work (project/run canonical store in slice 4, agent execution in slice 5) can resolve effective settings and know which project commands target without explicit `--id` flags.\n\nThe config surface covers keys implied by the master prompt: `prompt_review.enabled` (controls whether the optional `prompt_review` stage runs in the `standard` flow), default backend family, default model overrides, and validation strictness. The implementation stores configuration in `workspace.toml` using a structured TOML schema, resolves effective values through a defaults-then-override chain, and enforces fail-fast on unsupported workspace versions (invariant already partially present, now wired through all config-reading paths).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `workspace.toml` schema is extended with an optional `[settings]` table supporting at minimum these keys: `prompt_review.enabled` (bool, default `true`), `default_flow` (string, must be a valid `FlowPreset`, default `\"standard\"`), `default_backend` (string, optional), `default_model` (string, optional). Unknown keys in `[settings]` are preserved on round-trip (forward-compatible editing).\n- [ ] An `EffectiveConfig` struct in `workspace_governance` resolves the full configuration by merging persisted `workspace.toml` settings with compiled defaults. Every supported key has a typed accessor with a documented default value. `EffectiveConfig::load(base_dir)` is the single entry point for all config reads.\n- [ ] `ralph-burning config show` loads the workspace, checks the version (fail-fast on mismatch), and prints all effective settings as a human-readable TOML-like table showing each key, its effective value, and its source (`default` or `workspace.toml`).\n- [ ] `ralph-burning config get <key>` prints the effective value for a single key. Exits non-zero with a clear error for unknown keys.\n- [ ] `ralph-burning config set <key> <value>` validates the key name and value type, writes the updated value into `workspace.toml` under `[settings]`, and prints a confirmation. Exits non-zero for invalid keys or values (e.g., setting `default_flow` to an unknown preset).\n- [ ] `ralph-burning config edit` opens `workspace.toml` in `$EDITOR` (or `$VISUAL`, falling back to `vi`). After the editor exits, the file is re-validated; if validation fails, the user is warned on stderr and the command exits non-zero (but the file is not reverted — the user must fix manually).\n- [ ] `active-project` is a plain-text file in `.ralph-burning/` containing a single project ID (trimmed, no newline normalization issues). When absent, commands that require an active project fail with an explicit message naming `project select`.\n- [ ] `ralph-burning project select <id>` validates that the project directory `.ralph-burning/projects/<id>/` exists and contains `project.toml`, writes the ID to `active-project`, and prints a confirmation. Exits non-zero if the project does not exist.\n- [ ] A `resolve_active_project(base_dir) -> AppResult<ProjectId>` function in `workspace_governance` reads and validates `active-project`, returning a typed `ProjectId` or a descriptive error. This function is the single resolution point for all commands that operate on the current project.\n- [ ] All config and active-project commands check workspace version first and fail fast on unsupported versions (wiring the existing `ensure_supported_workspace_version` through the CLI path).\n- [ ] The filesystem adapter (`adapters/fs.rs`) gains methods for atomic config writes (write-to-temp-then-rename) and active-project file read/write, keeping side effects behind the adapter boundary.\n- [ ] Unit tests cover: `EffectiveConfig` default resolution, override merging, round-trip serialization of extended `workspace.toml`, unknown-key preservation, invalid key/value rejection, active-project read/write/missing cases.\n- [ ] Integration tests cover: `config show` output format, `config get` known and unknown keys, `config set` valid and invalid mutations, `project select` with existing and non-existing project directories.\n- [ ] Gherkin scenarios added to `tests/conformance/features/workspace_config.feature`: show effective config, get known key, get unknown key, set valid key, set invalid value, set invalid key, edit with valid result, edit with invalid result.\n- [ ] Gherkin scenarios added to `tests/conformance/features/active_project.feature`: select existing project, select non-existing project, resolve when no active project set, resolve after valid select.\n- [ ] `cargo test` and `cargo clippy --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings` pass after all changes.\n\n## Files to Modify/Create\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/shared/domain.rs` — extend `WorkspaceConfig` with optional `settings: WorkspaceSettings` field; add `WorkspaceSettings` struct with typed config fields and defaults\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/shared/error.rs` — add error variants: `UnknownConfigKey`, `InvalidConfigValue`, `NoActiveProject`, `ProjectNotFound`, `EditorFailed`\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/workspace_governance/mod.rs` — add `EffectiveConfig` struct with `load()`, `get()`, `set()` methods; add `resolve_active_project()` and `set_active_project()` functions; refactor config loading to use extended schema\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/workspace_governance/config.rs` — (new) effective config resolution logic, key registry, default values, validation of key names and value types\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/adapters/fs.rs` — add `write_atomic()`, `read_active_project()`, `write_active_project()`, `open_editor()` methods\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/cli/config.rs` — implement `show`, `get`, `set`, `edit` handlers replacing the current stubs\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/cli/project.rs` — implement `select` handler (other project subcommands remain stubs)\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit/config_test.rs` — unit tests for effective config resolution, merging, serialization, key validation\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit/active_project_test.rs` — unit tests for active-project read/write/missing\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/conformance/features/workspace_config.feature` — Gherkin scenarios for config commands\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/conformance/features/active_project.feature` — Gherkin scenarios for active project resolution\n\n## Dependencies\n- Requires: Loop 1 (workspace init, `WorkspaceConfig`, filesystem adapter) and Loop 2 (flow preset validation for `default_flow` config key)\n- Blocks: Slice 4 (project/run canonical store needs `resolve_active_project` and effective config), Slice 5 (agent execution needs default backend/model config resolution), Slice 6 (`run start` needs active project and effective config for prompt_review gate)\n\n---\n\nFILE /root/new-ralph-burning/.ralph/projects/ralph-burning-rewrite/loops/004-project-and-run-record-foundation/20260311194558-spec.md\n---\nartifact: spec\nloop: 4\nproject: ralph-burning-rewrite\nbackend: codex(gpt-5.4-xhigh)\nrole: planner\ncreated_at: 2026-03-11T19:45:58Z\n---\n\nI’m reviewing `prompt.md`, the completed loop specs, and recent git checkpoints to determine what is already covered and what the next unimplemented slice should be. First I’ll map the current planning artifacts against the roadmap and the codebase state so I don’t re-spec completed work.\nI’ve confirmed the branch is sitting just after Loop 3 planning, with loops 1 through 3 committed in git and conformance coverage matching those slices. Next I’m reading the actual spec artifacts and the current Rust modules to check whether roadmap step 4 has already been partially built or only stubbed.\nThe loop artifacts live under the hidden `.ralph/` planning workspace, not in the Rust crate itself. I’m reading those specs plus the current source modules now to determine whether the next slice is the canonical project/run store from roadmap step 4 or whether some of that was already pulled forward.\nThe approved specs line up cleanly with roadmap slices 1 through 3. I’m now checking the current `project_run_record`, `project` CLI, and `run` CLI surfaces to see whether any slice-4 behavior already exists, so the next spec only covers the actual gap.\nSlice 4 is still empty in code: `project_run_record` is only a stub, `project create/list/show/delete` are unimplemented, and every `run` subcommand still exits `NotYetImplemented`. I’m confirming there isn’t hidden project/run persistence elsewhere and then I’ll draft the next feature around that gap.\nI’ve verified there’s no hidden implementation beyond Loop 3. To tighten the next spec, I’m pulling the architecture notes for the `project_run_record` context from the repo docs so the acceptance criteria line up with the intended storage model and invariants, not just the roadmap headline.\nThe roadmap and architecture notes both point to the same next gap: `Project & Run Record`. I’m pulling the scenario notes around project creation and durable-history-vs-runtime-log separation so the spec includes the right invariants for failure handling and query behavior.\nI have enough to choose the slice. I’m doing one last pass over the shared error types and current storage helpers so the file list and failure-mode criteria match the crate’s existing structure instead of inventing a parallel design.\n# Feature: Project and Run Record Foundation\n\n## Description\nLoops 1 through 3 are complete: the rewrite already has workspace bootstrap, built-in flow discovery, stage-contract/rendering infrastructure, and workspace governance with effective config plus active-project resolution. The next missing slice is roadmap step 4: make `project_run_record` the durable source of truth by implementing canonical project storage, initial run/journal state, project CRUD, and read-only run query commands.\n\nCurrent HEAD still has `src/contexts/project_run_record/mod.rs` as a stub, `project create/list/show/delete` unimplemented, and all `run` commands unimplemented. This feature should fill that gap without re-planning completed flow, config, or active-project work.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `ralph-burning project create --id <id> --name <name> --prompt <file> --flow <flow-id>` validates workspace version, project ID, flow preset, prompt readability, and duplicate IDs before any filesystem mutation.\n- [ ] Successful project creation writes `.ralph-burning/projects/<project-id>/project.toml`, `prompt.md`, `run.json`, `journal.ndjson`, `sessions.json`, `history/payloads/`, `history/artifacts/`, `runtime/logs/`, `runtime/backend/`, `runtime/temp/`, `amendments/`, and `rollback/`.\n- [ ] `project.toml` persists immutable project metadata: `id`, `name`, fixed `flow`, copied prompt reference, prompt hash, creation timestamp, and durable status summary. Flow cannot be changed after creation by any CLI or store path.\n- [ ] `run.json` persists canonical run state only: active run pointer, run status, optional stage cursor, cycle history, completion rounds, rollback-point metadata, amendment-queue state, and status summary. It must not infer state from artifacts or logs.\n- [ ] `journal.ndjson` is append-only, sequence-ordered, and initialized with a `project_created` event. Queries derive state from canonical run state plus journal, never from Markdown scans.\n- [ ] `sessions.json` initializes as a valid empty session store, separate from durable history.\n- [ ] `project create` is atomic. If prompt copy, snapshot write, or journal initialization fails, the new project is not visible to `project list/show`, no partial canonical files remain exposed, and `.ralph-burning/active-project` is unchanged.\n- [ ] Duplicate project creation fails non-zero with a clear error and leaves existing project state unchanged.\n- [ ] `project create` does not implicitly select the new project; active-project mutation remains the job of the already-implemented `project select`.\n- [ ] `ralph-burning project list` reads canonical project records, not raw directory names, and shows enough summary data to identify each project plus whether it is the active selection.\n- [ ] `ralph-burning project show [<id>]` shows explicit project data when `<id>` is provided and otherwise resolves the active project through workspace governance. Output includes flow, prompt hash/reference, created timestamp, run summary, and rollback summary.\n- [ ] `ralph-burning project delete <id>` deletes only projects with no active run. If the deleted project was selected, `.ralph-burning/active-project` is cleared only after the delete succeeds. If delete fails after validation, the project remains addressable and the active-project pointer is unchanged.\n- [ ] Add payload/artifact store models and enumeration APIs for durable history. If a payload write succeeds but its artifact companion write/index fails, `run history` and `run tail` must not expose a partial durable-history record.\n- [ ] Runtime logs are stored and queried separately from durable history. Runtime-log write failures must not fabricate, remove, or reorder durable history.\n- [ ] `ralph-burning run status` reads canonical state for the active project and reports either “not started” or the persisted run snapshot without inferring from artifacts.\n- [ ] `ralph-burning run history` shows durable history only: journal events plus payload/artifact records in canonical order. Runtime logs never appear there.\n- [ ] `ralph-burning run tail` shows durable history only by default, and `ralph-burning run tail --logs` appends the newest runtime logs after the durable section without changing the durable-history portion.\n- [ ] Corrupt or inconsistent canonical files (`project.toml`, `run.json`, `journal.ndjson`, payload/artifact indexes) fail fast with file-specific errors. Commands must not fall back to rendered Markdown or directory scans when canonical state is invalid.\n- [ ] Introduce `ProjectStorePort`, `JournalStorePort`, `ArtifactStorePort`, and `RuntimeLogStorePort` boundaries inside `contexts/project_run_record`, with filesystem-backed adapters using atomic writes/renames.\n- [ ] Add domain/unit tests for immutable flow, journal sequencing, and history/log separation; service tests with fake ports; adapter contract tests for filesystem round trips and corruption visibility; and CLI integration tests for project CRUD plus run queries.\n- [ ] Add public Gherkin coverage for project creation, duplicate IDs, immutable flow, list/show/delete behavior, no-active-run status, durable-history-only queries, and `run tail --logs` separation semantics.\n- [ ] `cargo test` and `cargo clippy --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings` pass.\n\n## Files to Modify/Create\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/project_run_record/mod.rs` - expose the context surface, core ports, and public use cases\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/project_run_record/model.rs` - define project records, run snapshots, journal events, payload/artifact records, runtime-log records, and rollback metadata\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/project_run_record/service.rs` - implement create/list/show/delete and run query use cases with invariant checks\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/project_run_record/queries.rs` - build canonical read models for status, history, and tail\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/project_run_record/journal.rs` - define append/read ordering and sequence validation for `journal.ndjson`\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/adapters/fs.rs` - add atomic project staging, canonical snapshot reads/writes, NDJSON append helpers, prompt hashing, and active-project clearing on delete\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/cli/project.rs` - replace stubs for `create`, `list`, `show`, and `delete` while preserving existing `select`\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/cli/run.rs` - implement `status`, `history`, and `tail`; keep `start`, `resume`, and `rollback` as later-slice work\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/shared/error.rs` - add duplicate-project, corrupt-record, invalid-prompt, active-run-delete, and journal-sequence error variants\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/conformance/features/project_records.feature` - public scenarios for project CRUD and immutable flow\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/conformance/features/run_queries.feature` - public scenarios for status/history/tail and runtime-log separation\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit/project_run_record_test.rs` - domain and service tests for project/run invariants\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit/journal_test.rs` - journal ordering, corruption, and append semantics\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit/query_test.rs` - durable-history and runtime-log separation tests\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/cli.rs` - CLI integration coverage for project and run query commands\n\n## Dependencies\n- Requires: Loop 1 foundation, Loop 2 stage contract registry and deterministic rendering, Loop 3 workspace governance effective config and active project resolution\n- Blocks: Agent-driven `run start` orchestration, resume/retry/rollback semantics, and requirements-to-project handoff\n\n---\n\nFILE /root/new-ralph-burning/.ralph/projects/ralph-burning-rewrite/loops/005-agent-execution-facade/20260311214221-spec.md\n---\nartifact: spec\nloop: 5\nproject: ralph-burning-rewrite\nbackend: claude(opus)\nrole: planner\ncreated_at: 2026-03-11T21:42:21Z\n---\n\nNow I have a clear picture. Loops 1-4 covered delivery roadmap items 1-4. The next item is **#5: Agent Execution Facade with Structured-Output Guarantee**.\n\n# Feature: Agent Execution Facade\n\n## Description\nImplement the `agent_execution` bounded context as the uniform invocation layer for all backend interactions. This context provides a structured-output guarantee: every backend call either produces a validated stage-payload-compatible result or fails with an explicit failure class. The facade abstracts backend families (Claude, Codex, OpenRouter), resolves per-role model/backend selection, enforces timeout and cancellation semantics, normalizes raw backend output into a standard invocation envelope, and preserves raw output in runtime logs. This is a prerequisite for `run start` (roadmap item 6) and must define clean port boundaries so actual backend adapters can be plugged in without changing the facade contract.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Define `BackendSpec` and `ModelSpec` types representing a backend family + model identifier, with display names and capability metadata\n- [ ] Define `BackendRole` enum mapping stage requirements to backend selection (e.g., `Planner`, `Implementer`, `Reviewer`, `QaValidator`, `CompletionJudge`) with per-role default backend/model\n- [ ] Implement `BackendResolver` that resolves the effective backend+model for a given role using precedence: explicit model override → project config → workspace default → role default\n- [ ] Define `InvocationRequest` struct containing: target stage contract reference, role, resolved backend+model, prompt/context payload, timeout duration, and cancellation token\n- [ ] Define `InvocationEnvelope` (the normalized result) containing: raw output reference, parsed structured payload (`serde_json::Value`), invocation metadata (duration, token counts, model used, attempt number), and timestamp\n- [ ] Define `AgentExecutionPort` trait with async methods: `check_capability(backend, stage_contract) -> Result<()>`, `check_availability(backend) -> Result<()>`, `invoke(request) -> Result<InvocationEnvelope>`, and `cancel(invocation_id) -> Result<()>`\n- [ ] Implement `AgentExecutionService` that orchestrates: capability verification → availability check → invocation → raw output preservation → structured output extraction → envelope construction\n- [ ] Map every failure scenario to the correct `FailureClass`: transport errors → `TransportFailure`, malformed output → `SchemaValidationFailure`, semantic issues → `DomainValidationFailure`, deadline exceeded → `Timeout`, user/system cancel → `Cancellation`\n- [ ] Cancellation token propagation: when cancel is signaled, immediately halt any in-progress invocation and return `FailureClass::Cancellation` — no further retries\n- [ ] Timeout enforcement: invocations that exceed their deadline are terminated and return `FailureClass::Timeout` — no further retries for this attempt\n- [ ] Raw backend output is written to `runtime/backend/` under the project directory via `RuntimeLogStorePort` (or a new `RawOutputPort`); never promoted to durable history\n- [ ] Session reuse: define `SessionPolicy` (enum: `NewSession`, `ReuseIfAllowed`) on `InvocationRequest`; the port checks backend/role support before reusing\n- [ ] `sessions.json` integration: persist and load session metadata per project for backends that support session continuity\n- [ ] Implement a `StubBackendAdapter` (in `adapters/`) that implements `AgentExecutionPort` with deterministic canned responses for each stage contract — sufficient for testing the full invocation pipeline without real API calls\n- [ ] Wire `AgentExecutionService` into the CLI module structure (no new CLI commands, but the service must be constructible from the existing adapter/config wiring)\n- [ ] Unit tests: capability check success/failure, resolution precedence, timeout behavior, cancellation propagation, failure class mapping, envelope construction, session policy enforcement\n- [ ] Adapter contract test for `StubBackendAdapter` verifying it satisfies `AgentExecutionPort`\n\n## Files to Modify/Create\n- `src/shared/domain.rs` — Add `BackendSpec`, `ModelSpec`, `BackendRole`, `SessionPolicy` types\n- `src/contexts/agent_execution/mod.rs` — Module root with re-exports, `CONTEXT_NAME`\n- `src/contexts/agent_execution/model.rs` — `InvocationRequest`, `InvocationEnvelope`, `InvocationMetadata`, `CancellationToken`, `CapabilityCheck` types\n- `src/contexts/agent_execution/service.rs` — `AgentExecutionService` orchestration logic, `AgentExecutionPort` trait, `BackendResolver` with precedence chain\n- `src/contexts/agent_execution/session.rs` — `SessionManager` for session reuse logic and `sessions.json` read/write\n- `src/adapters/stub_backend.rs` — `StubBackendAdapter` implementing `AgentExecutionPort` with canned payloads per stage\n- `src/adapters/mod.rs` — Register `stub_backend` module\n- `src/shared/error.rs` — Add agent execution error variants (`BackendUnavailable`, `CapabilityMismatch`, `InvocationFailed`, `InvocationTimeout`, `InvocationCancelled`)\n- `tests/unit/agent_execution_test.rs` — Unit tests for service, resolver, failure mapping\n- `tests/unit/stub_backend_test.rs` — Adapter contract tests\n- `tests/unit.rs` — Register new test modules\n\n## Dependencies\n- Requires: Loop 4 (Project and Run Record Foundation) — for `RuntimeLogStorePort`, project directory structure, `FailureClass` enum, stage contract types\n- Requires: Loop 2 (Stage Contract Registry) — for `StageContract` and `StageId` used in capability checks and payload validation\n- Requires: Loop 3 (Workspace Governance) — for workspace config defaults (`default_backend`, `default_model`) used in resolution precedence\n- Blocks: Loop 6 (Standard preset vertical path / `run start` end-to-end) — which needs the execution facade to drive stage invocations\n- Blocks: Loop 7 (Retry/remediation) — which needs failure class semantics from this facade\n\n---\n\nFILE /root/new-ralph-burning/.ralph/projects/ralph-burning-rewrite/loops/006-standard-preset-run-start-orchestration/20260311221639-spec.md\n---\nartifact: spec\nloop: 6\nproject: ralph-burning-rewrite\nbackend: codex(gpt-5.4-xhigh)\nrole: planner\ncreated_at: 2026-03-11T22:16:39Z\n---\n\nI’m reviewing `prompt.md`, the completed loop specs, and recent git checkpoints to determine what is already built and what the next missing feature slice should be. After that I’ll map the current implementation against the roadmap and write the next spec in the required format.\nI’m gathering the project artifacts now: the master prompt, completed loop specs, and checkpoint history. Then I’ll verify the codebase aligns with those completed loops so I don’t re-plan something already present.\n`prompt.md` is not at the workspace root, so I’m locating the actual planning inputs and narrowing the inspection to the rewrite project and loop artifacts. After that I’ll read the completed specs and compare them to the current code paths.\nI’ve got the loop spec locations and confirmed the branch is currently at loop 5 complete. Next I’m reading the rewrite project’s own `prompt.md` plus the five approved specs and then checking the implementation surface for run orchestration gaps.\nThe codebase confirms loops 1 through 5: workspace init/config, flow registry, project/run record queries, stage contract validation/rendering, and the agent-execution facade are all present. I’m reading the approved specs directly now to pin the exact handoff boundary before choosing the next slice.\nThe likely handoff is roadmap step 6, but I’m verifying that nothing from `run start` orchestration or standard-flow persistence already landed outside the obvious CLI stub. I’m checking the loop-5 checkpoint diff and the current test inventory for any hidden vertical-path coverage.\nI’ve confirmed the missing surface is real: no `run start`, no run-orchestration service, and no conformance coverage for stage execution. I’m inspecting the existing storage and contract APIs now so the spec can target the exact integration seam instead of inventing a parallel design.\nI have the seam now: the project can validate contracts and invoke stub backends, but there is still no composition engine that moves a run through stages and persists the success path. I’m checking the existing shared domain types one last time so the spec names the right state objects and doesn’t duplicate what’s already there.\n# Feature: Standard Preset Run Start Orchestration\n\n## Description\nLoops 1 through 5 are already complete in the approved specs and reflected in git checkpoints through the current loop-5 planning head: the rewrite has workspace/bootstrap commands, fixed flow presets, stage contracts and deterministic renderers, effective config plus active-project resolution, canonical project/run records and query commands, and the agent-execution facade with stub backend support. The next missing roadmap slice is step 6: implement the first real workflow engine behind `ralph-burning run start`.\n\nThis feature should add the straight-through `standard` preset execution path by wiring `workflow_composition`, `project_run_record`, and `agent_execution` together. It should execute enabled standard stages in canonical order, persist validated payloads and rendered artifacts at durable stage boundaries, and update `run.json` plus `journal.ndjson` as the source of truth. It should not yet add retry/remediation, resume, amendment-queue behavior, or non-standard flow execution.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `ralph-burning run start` validates workspace version, active project selection, canonical project record integrity, and canonical run snapshot integrity before any mutation.\n- [ ] `run start` is allowed only when the project snapshot is `not_started` with no active run; running, paused, failed, or completed snapshots fail explicitly and never create a duplicate run.\n- [ ] This slice supports only projects with flow `standard`; `quick_dev`, `docs_change`, and `ci_improvement` fail with an explicit unsupported-for-now error and leave all canonical state unchanged.\n- [ ] The standard stage plan is derived from the existing flow definition in canonical order and honors `prompt_review.enabled`: when enabled, the run starts at `prompt_review`; when disabled, it starts at `planning` and writes no `prompt_review` history.\n- [ ] Before persisting `run_started`, the engine resolves stage-to-role/backend/model targets for every stage it will execute and performs capability plus availability preflight. If any preflight check fails, `run.json`, `journal.ndjson`, payloads, artifacts, sessions, and the active-project pointer remain unchanged.\n- [ ] On successful start, the engine creates exactly one new run ID and persists `run.json` with `status=running`, `active_run.stage_cursor` at the first executable stage, `cycle=1`, `attempt=1`, and `completion_round=1`, then appends `run_started` and first `stage_entered` journal events.\n- [ ] Stage-to-role mapping is deterministic and centralized: `prompt_review`/`planning` use `Planner`, `implementation` uses `Implementer`, `qa`/`acceptance_qa` use `QaValidator`, `review` uses `Reviewer`, and `completion_panel`/`final_review` use `CompletionJudge`.\n- [ ] Every stage invocation goes through `AgentExecutionService`; raw backend output is persisted only under `runtime/backend/`, and operational runtime logs are persisted only under `runtime/logs/`.\n- [ ] A stage is successful only after the validated payload JSON, rendered Markdown artifact, `stage_completed` journal event, and updated `run.json` / next-stage cursor are committed as one logical durable boundary. If payload write succeeds but artifact, journal, or snapshot persistence fails, the stage remains uncommitted: no paired history record is visible, no `stage_completed` event exists, and the cursor stays at the prior durable boundary.\n- [ ] On straight-through success with the stub backend, `run start` executes all enabled standard stages in order and ends with `run.json` status `completed`, `active_run=null`, `completion_rounds=1`, monotonic cycle/attempt values, and a terminal `run_completed` journal event persisted before any best-effort cleanup.\n- [ ] `run history` and `run tail` after a successful run show one payload/artifact pair per completed stage in canonical stage order and never include raw backend output or runtime logs unless `run tail --logs` is used.\n- [ ] This slice performs no retries. Any transport failure, schema-validation failure, domain-validation failure, timeout, cancellation, or non-passing QA/review outcome halts the run immediately and executes no later stages.\n- [ ] Failure invariants are explicit: if failure happens before `stage_entered`, that stage produces no journal or durable-history records; if failure happens after `stage_entered` but before successful commit, that stage may retain raw diagnostics only, but it has no payload/artifact pair, no `stage_completed`, and the run persists a failed state at that stage boundary.\n- [ ] Non-passing outcomes in `qa`, `review`, `completion_panel`, `acceptance_qa`, or `final_review` are terminal for this slice: the run is marked failed, no amendment-queue items are created, no completion round advances, and no remediation or resume logic is attempted.\n- [ ] Runtime-log append failures are cosmetic only: they must not fabricate, remove, or reorder durable history, and they must not turn an already committed stage into a failed durable-history state.\n- [ ] Add unit/service tests for stage-plan selection, preflight short-circuiting, happy-path completion, and atomic stage-commit failure handling.\n- [ ] Add CLI integration and Gherkin coverage for: successful standard `run start`, prompt-review-disabled start, active-run rejection, unsupported-flow rejection, preflight failure with no mutation, and mid-stage failure without partial durable-history exposure.\n- [ ] `cargo test` and `cargo clippy --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings` pass.\n\n## Files to Modify/Create\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/cli/run.rs` - implement `run start` and wire the orchestration dependencies while leaving `resume` and `rollback` for later slices\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/workflow_composition/mod.rs` - export the run engine and standard-stage-plan helpers\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs` - add the standard-flow orchestration engine, stage-to-role mapping, preflight checks, and progression loop\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/project_run_record/model.rs` - extend run and journal models for run lifecycle persistence and failed-stage summaries\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/project_run_record/service.rs` - add mutation use cases for run start, stage commit, stage failure, and terminal completion\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/project_run_record/journal.rs` - add lifecycle event builders and sequence helpers for `run_started`, `stage_entered`, `stage_completed`, `run_completed`, and `run_failed`\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/adapters/fs.rs` - add run snapshot writes, atomic payload/artifact pair persistence, journal append sequencing, and runtime-log writing\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/shared/error.rs` - add explicit orchestration and unsupported-flow errors for `run start`\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit.rs` - register new workflow-engine tests\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit/workflow_engine_test.rs` - cover happy path, preflight short-circuiting, and failure invariants\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit/project_run_record_test.rs` - extend durable stage-commit and failed-run snapshot coverage\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/cli.rs` - add CLI integration coverage for `run start`\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/conformance/features/run_start_standard.feature` - add public scenarios for standard `run start`\n\n## Dependencies\n- Requires: Loops 2 through 5 (stage contracts/renderers, workspace governance, project/run record foundation, and agent execution facade)\n- Blocks: retry/remediation plus `run resume`, completion/acceptance/final-review amendment behavior, and non-standard flow execution support\n\n---\n\nFILE /root/new-ralph-burning/.ralph/projects/ralph-burning-rewrite/loops/007-retry-remediation-resume-and-failure-class/20260311235426-spec.md\n---\nartifact: spec\nloop: 7\nproject: ralph-burning-rewrite\nbackend: claude(opus)\nrole: planner\ncreated_at: 2026-03-11T23:54:26Z\n---\n\nNow I have a thorough understanding of the codebase. Let me write the spec for the next feature.\n\n# Feature: Retry, Remediation, Resume, and Failure Class Semantics\n\n## Description\nImplement the retry/remediation layer, run resume capability, prompt review pause behavior, and failure-class-driven retry policies for the workflow engine. Currently (Loop 6), any stage failure immediately terminates the run. This feature adds: (1) configurable retry policies mapped to each `FailureClass`, with per-stage attempt tracking; (2) remediation cycles when QA or Review stages return `RequestChanges`, looping back to the implementation stage with an incremented cycle number; (3) `run resume` to continue a failed or paused run from the last durable stage boundary; (4) prompt review pause semantics where `readiness.ready == false` pauses the run for user revision. These behaviors are required by delivery roadmap item 7 and core invariants: \"Cancellation and timeout must immediately halt retries,\" \"Resume is allowed only from durable stage boundaries,\" and \"Cycle and completion round numbers are monotonic and independent.\"\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] A `RetryPolicy` struct maps each `FailureClass` to max attempts and terminal/retryable classification. Default policies: `TransportFailure` → max 3 attempts; `SchemaValidationFailure` → max 2; `DomainValidationFailure` → max 2; `Timeout` → max 2; `Cancellation` → terminal (0 retries); `QaReviewOutcomeFailure` → not retried (triggers remediation or terminal depending on outcome).\n- [ ] The engine retry loop increments `StageCursor.attempt` on each retry and emits `StageFailed` + `StageEntered` journal events per attempt. Cancellation signal during a retry loop immediately halts all further retries for that stage.\n- [ ] When a QA or Review stage (but NOT `CompletionPanel`, `AcceptanceQa`, or `FinalReview`) returns `RequestChanges`, the engine persists the validation payload/artifact, emits a `CycleAdvanced` journal event, increments the cycle number, and loops execution back to the `Implementation` stage. Follow-up amendments from the review payload are passed as invocation context to the re-executed implementation stage.\n- [ ] When a QA or Review stage returns `Rejected`, the run fails terminally with `QaReviewOutcomeFailure`. When `ConditionallyApproved`, execution continues to the next stage and the `follow_up_or_amendments` are appended to the `amendment_queue` in the run snapshot.\n- [ ] Maximum remediation cycles per run is configurable (default 3). Exceeding the limit fails the run with a `RemediationExhausted` error.\n- [ ] `StageContract::evaluate_permissive` performs schema validation + semantic validation + rendering WITHOUT the outcome check, returning `ValidatedBundle` even for non-passing validation payloads. The engine calls this, persists the bundle, then separately inspects the `ReviewOutcome` to decide remediation vs continue vs fail.\n- [ ] `run resume` reads the snapshot (must be `Failed` or `Paused`) and journal, identifies completed stages via `StageCompleted` journal events, sets status back to `Running`, restores `active_run` with the cursor at the first incomplete stage (attempt reset to 1), appends a `RunResumed` journal event, and continues execution. The run_id is preserved across resume.\n- [ ] `run resume` on a `NotStarted`, `Running`, or `Completed` snapshot returns a clear error.\n- [ ] When the `PromptReview` stage produces a payload with `readiness.ready == false`, the engine persists the payload/artifact, sets `RunStatus::Paused`, clears `active_run`, and returns with a descriptive message. The user may revise the prompt and run `ralph-burning run resume` to continue from the `Planning` stage.\n- [ ] `run start` on a project with status `Failed` or `Paused` returns a clear error directing the user to `run resume`.\n- [ ] New `JournalEventType` variants: `StageFailed` (stage_id, cycle, attempt, failure_class, message, will_retry: bool) and `RunResumed` (run_id, resume_stage, cycle). Existing `CycleAdvanced` event builder is implemented (builder already referenced in enum but never constructed).\n- [ ] `StubBackendAdapter` gains `with_transient_failure(stage_id, fail_count)` that fails the first N invocations for a stage and then succeeds, enabling retry and remediation test scenarios.\n- [ ] Unit tests cover: retry exhaustion → run failure; retry success on second attempt; remediation cycle triggered by QA `RequestChanges`; remediation limit exceeded; resume from failed run skips completed stages; resume from paused prompt-review run; cancellation halts retry loop; `ConditionallyApproved` queues amendments and proceeds.\n- [ ] State invariant: after any failure mode (retry exhaustion, remediation exhaustion, cancellation during retry, resume validation failure), the run snapshot is in a consistent terminal or resumable state — `Failed` with `active_run == None`, or `Paused` with `active_run == None`. No partial `Running` state is left behind.\n\n## Files to Modify/Create\n- `src/contexts/workflow_composition/retry_policy.rs` (new) — `RetryPolicy` struct with `FailureClass` → max-attempts mapping, `default_policy()`, `is_retryable()`, `max_remediation_cycles()`.\n- `src/contexts/workflow_composition/mod.rs` — Export new `retry_policy` module.\n- `src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs` — Major refactor: add `execute_standard_run_with_retry()` (or extend existing), implement per-stage retry loop with attempt tracking, remediation cycle logic (QA/Review → Implementation loop-back with cycle increment), prompt review pause handling, and `resume_standard_run()` entry point that loads journal, skips completed stages, and continues.\n- `src/contexts/workflow_composition/contracts.rs` — Add `evaluate_permissive()` method that skips `check_outcome()`, returning `ValidatedBundle` for non-passing outcomes.\n- `src/contexts/project_run_record/model.rs` — Add `StageFailed` and `RunResumed` to `JournalEventType` enum.\n- `src/contexts/project_run_record/journal.rs` — Add `stage_failed_event()`, `run_resumed_event()`, and `cycle_advanced_event()` builder functions.\n- `src/cli/run.rs` — Implement `handle_resume()` wiring: validate workspace/project, check snapshot status is Failed or Paused, call `engine::resume_standard_run()`. Update `handle_start()` to reject `Failed`/`Paused` status with message directing to `run resume`.\n- `src/shared/error.rs` — Add `ResumeFailed { reason: String }`, `RemediationExhausted { cycle: u32, max: u32 }` variants to `AppError`.\n- `src/adapters/stub_backend.rs` — Add `with_transient_failure(stage_id, fail_count)` using internal `AtomicU32` counter to track per-stage invocation attempts and fail the first N.\n- `tests/unit/retry_policy_test.rs` (new) — Tests for retry policy defaults, retryable classification, terminal classification.\n- `tests/unit/workflow_engine_test.rs` — Add test cases for retry loops, remediation cycles, resume behavior, prompt review pause, cancellation during retry, amendment queueing on ConditionallyApproved.\n\n## Dependencies\n- Requires: Loop 6 (Standard Preset Run Start Orchestration) — provides the straight-through engine, stage commit logic, fail_run helper, and stub backend\n- Blocks: Loop 8 (Completion/Acceptance/Final-Review Behavior + Amendment Queue) — completion panel semantics, amendment processing, and acceptance/final-review remediation depend on the retry/remediation/resume infrastructure built here\n\n---\n\nFILE /root/new-ralph-burning/.ralph/projects/ralph-burning-rewrite/loops/008-completion-rounds-late-stage-acceptance-and/20260312010412-spec.md\n---\nartifact: spec\nloop: 8\nproject: ralph-burning-rewrite\nbackend: codex(gpt-5.4-xhigh)\nrole: planner\ncreated_at: 2026-03-12T01:04:12Z\n---\n\nI’m reviewing `prompt.md`, completed loop specs, and git checkpoints to determine what is already delivered and what the next missing feature should be. After that I’ll write a spec only for the first unimplemented roadmap slice.\nI have the checkpoint sequence; next I’m narrowing to the planning inputs and current implementation surface so I can tell whether roadmap step 8 is still actually missing or partly landed already.\nThe code already contains some stage names and state fields for later roadmap items, so I’m checking whether those are just type scaffolding or actual delivered behavior before choosing the next feature.\nI’m past the roadmap handoff and into the code now. The key question is whether loop 8 is still missing or whether completion-panel/amendment behavior already leaked into loop 7’s implementation, which would push the next feature further down the roadmap.\nLoop 7 is more substantial than the tracker implies: retry, remediation to implementation, pause/resume, and amendment queue accumulation are already in the engine. I’m checking the remaining helpers and tests to see which parts of roadmap step 8 are still absent rather than already delivered.\nThe current engine already executes through `completion_panel`, `acceptance_qa`, and `final_review`, but it appears to treat them with generic validation semantics. I’m verifying whether any feature-specific completion-round logic, final-review gating, or amendment-queue processing is actually implemented, because that decides whether the next spec is loop 8 hardening or the next preset family.\nI’ve confirmed loop 7 from the actual diff: it added exactly the retry/resume/remediation slice. What remains around step 8 is not “run the later stages” but “give those later stages their own state machine”: completion rounds, amendment-queue lifecycle, and completion/final-review semantics are still generic or stubbed.\nI need one more pass through the legacy reference artifacts, because the roadmap only names step 8 while the current rewrite already has generic versions of those stages. I’m using the old specs only to recover the intended semantics for completion rounds and amendment handling, not to plan around legacy storage or protocol.\n# Feature: Completion Rounds, Late-Stage Acceptance, and Durable Amendments\n\n## Description\nApproved loop artifacts `001` through `007` and checkpoint history through `4b10f4e` show the rewrite has completed the roadmap through retry, remediation, pause/resume, and failure-class handling. The next missing slice is roadmap step 8. The current standard-flow engine already executes `completion_panel`, `acceptance_qa`, and `final_review`, but it still treats them as generic validation stages: `completion_rounds` never advances beyond `1`, `StageCursor::advance_completion_round` and `JournalEventType::CompletionRoundAdvanced` are unused, `AmendmentQueued` and `processed_count` are unused, `projects/<id>/amendments/` is only scaffolding, and a run can currently complete while `amendment_queue.pending` is non-empty. This feature should add the real late-stage state machine for the standard preset: completion-round advancement, durable amendment queue persistence/application, and stage-specific continue-vs-complete behavior for `completion_panel`, `acceptance_qa`, and `final_review`, without re-implementing loops 1-7 or enabling non-standard flows yet.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Loop-7 behavior remains unchanged for `qa` and `review`: their `RequestChanges` remediation path still advances work cycles directly back to `implementation`, and the new logic applies only to `completion_panel`, `acceptance_qa`, and `final_review`.\n- [ ] Late-stage transition rules are explicit and stage-specific: `completion_panel` `Approved` advances to `acceptance_qa`; `acceptance_qa` `Approved` advances to `final_review` when the flow definition enables final review and otherwise completes the run; `final_review` `Approved` completes the run; `Rejected` at any late stage fails the run terminally with `QaReviewOutcomeFailure`.\n- [ ] `ConditionallyApproved` or `RequestChanges` at any late stage does not silently proceed and does not terminally fail; after the late-stage payload/artifact pair is durably committed, the engine queues every `follow_up_or_amendments` item as a durable amendment, emits `amendment_queued` journal events, emits one `completion_round_advanced` journal event, and moves the cursor to `planning` for the next completion round.\n- [ ] On a `completion_round_advanced` transition, `StageCursor.completion_round` increments, `attempt` resets to `1`, the next stage becomes `planning`, and `cycle` stays unchanged at that boundary. `run.json.completion_rounds` tracks the highest round reached and remains monotonic independently of `cycle_history`.\n- [ ] When the next completion round successfully leaves `planning` and re-enters `implementation`, the engine emits `cycle_advanced`, increments the work-cycle number, and records the new cycle in `cycle_history`. Completion-round continuation must therefore advance completion round first and work cycle only when new implementation work actually begins.\n- [ ] Queued amendments are persisted under `projects/<id>/amendments/` using atomic writes and a typed canonical record that includes at least amendment id, source stage, source cycle, source completion round, body, and created timestamp. `run.json` stores the same queue in structured form; raw `serde_json::Value` placeholders are no longer the canonical queue model in this slice.\n- [ ] Pending queued amendments are injected into the next `planning` invocation in deterministic order. They are marked processed and removed from pending on-disk state only after the `planning` stage commit succeeds; planning invocation failure or planning commit failure must leave them pending and reusable on `run resume`.\n- [ ] `JournalEventType::CompletionRoundAdvanced` and `JournalEventType::AmendmentQueued` have concrete builders and are emitted in canonical order after the source late-stage commit. Public `run history`/`run tail` output includes those events without ever treating amendment files or runtime logs as durable history artifacts.\n- [ ] `run_completed` may be persisted only when both the structured amendment queue and the `amendments/` directory contain no pending items. A late-stage conditional approval must never allow a completed snapshot with leftover queued amendments.\n- [ ] `run resume` reconstructs pending amendments and the current completion round from canonical state and resumes from the first incomplete durable stage without duplicating already-processed amendments or losing queued ones.\n- [ ] Failure invariant: if amendment persistence fails before any `amendment_queued` event is committed, no queue entry becomes visible in `run.json` and no `completion_round_advanced` event is written.\n- [ ] Failure invariant: if some amendment files and `amendment_queued` events are durable but snapshot or cursor advancement fails afterward, those amendments remain pending and discoverable for resume; the run must end in a non-completed state with `active_run == null`.\n- [ ] Failure invariant: if completion is otherwise ready but pending amendments are detected during terminalization, completion is blocked and the run remains resumable; that guard must not delete, drain, or silently mark any pending amendment as processed.\n- [ ] Conformance and unit coverage are added for: completion-panel-driven continuation into round 2, acceptance-QA-driven continuation, final-review-driven continuation, terminal rejection at late stages, successful completion after a second round, resume with pending late-stage amendments, and the completion guard that blocks success while amendments remain queued.\n- [ ] `quick_dev`, `docs_change`, and `ci_improvement` remain unsupported in `run start` after this slice; this feature hardens only the standard-flow late-stage semantics.\n\n## Files to Modify/Create\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs` - add late-stage transition table, completion-round advancement, planning restart, amendment injection/drain, and completion guard\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/workflow_composition/mod.rs` - route acceptance/final-review behavior through flow-definition metadata instead of generic hard-coded assumptions\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/shared/domain.rs` - make cursor round/cycle transitions explicit for late-stage restart boundaries\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/project_run_record/model.rs` - add typed queued-amendment records and finalize journal event enum usage for completion-round/amendment events\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/project_run_record/journal.rs` - add builders for `completion_round_advanced` and `amendment_queued`\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/project_run_record/service.rs` - add ports/use-cases for reading, writing, draining, and reconciling durable amendment queue state\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/adapters/fs.rs` - implement filesystem-backed amendment queue persistence under `projects/<id>/amendments/`\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/shared/error.rs` - add explicit amendment-queue and completion-guard error variants\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit/workflow_engine_test.rs` - cover completion-round restarts, queue drain/apply behavior, and late-stage failure invariants\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit/journal_test.rs` - cover new journal event builders and ordering expectations\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit/adapter_contract_test.rs` - cover atomic amendment queue persistence and non-lossy failure behavior\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/cli.rs` - extend CLI-level assertions for round advancement, resume, and blocked completion\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/conformance/features/run_completion_rounds.feature` - add public scenarios for completion rounds, late-stage amendments, and blocked completion\n\n## Dependencies\n- Requires: Loop 7 (Retry, Remediation, Resume, and Failure Class Semantics)\n- Blocks: Non-standard preset execution on the shared engine (`quick_dev`, `docs_change`, `ci_improvement`)\n\n---\n\nFILE /root/new-ralph-burning/.ralph/projects/ralph-burning-rewrite/loops/009-docs-change-and-ci-improvement-flow-execution/20260312185042-spec.md\n---\nartifact: spec\nloop: 9\nproject: ralph-burning-rewrite\nbackend: claude(opus)\nrole: planner\ncreated_at: 2026-03-12T18:50:42Z\n---\n\nNow I have a complete picture of the codebase. The delivery roadmap clearly indicates Loop 9 should be **roadmap item 9: \"docs and CI preset integration on same engine\"**. The engine is currently hardcoded for the standard flow with explicit references to `StageId::Planning`, `StageId::Implementation`, etc. I need to plan the generalization.\n\n# Feature: Docs Change and CI Improvement Flow Execution\n\n## Description\nGeneralize the workflow engine to execute `docs_change` and `ci_improvement` flow presets on the same orchestration core that currently drives the `standard` flow. Today, `execute_standard_run` and `resume_standard_run` contain hardcoded references to standard-flow stage identifiers (`Planning`, `Implementation`, `PromptReview`, `CompletionPanel`, `AcceptanceQa`, `FinalReview`). This feature introduces a `FlowSemantics` descriptor that maps each flow preset's structural roles (planning stage, execution stage, remediation target, late stages, amendment injection point) so the engine can orchestrate any built-in flow without per-flow branching. The CLI `run start` and `run resume` commands are updated to accept `docs_change` and `ci_improvement` projects, and new conformance scenarios verify end-to-end behavior for both presets.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] A `FlowSemantics` struct is introduced that captures per-flow structural roles: `planning_stage` (the stage that receives amendment injection and drains amendments after commit), `execution_stage` (the stage that remediation cycles restart from), `remediation_trigger_stages` (stages whose `RequestChanges` outcome triggers a remediation cycle, analogous to today's `is_remediation_stage`), `late_stages` (stages whose `RequestChanges`/`ConditionallyApproved` outcomes trigger completion-round advancement), and `prompt_review_stage` (optional, for flows that include prompt review).\n- [ ] `FlowSemantics` is derivable from a `FlowPreset` via a `flow_semantics(preset: FlowPreset) -> FlowSemantics` function. For `docs_change`: planning=`DocsPlan`, execution=`DocsUpdate`, remediation_triggers=[`DocsValidation`, `Review`], late_stages=[], prompt_review=None. For `ci_improvement`: planning=`CiPlan`, execution=`CiUpdate`, remediation_triggers=[`CiValidation`, `Review`], late_stages=[], prompt_review=None. For `standard`: planning=`Planning`, execution=`Implementation`, remediation_triggers=[`Qa`, `Review`], late_stages=[`CompletionPanel`, `AcceptanceQa`, `FinalReview`], prompt_review=Some(`PromptReview`).\n- [ ] The engine functions `execute_standard_run`, `execute_standard_run_with_retry`, `execute_standard_run_internal`, `resume_standard_run`, and `resume_standard_run_with_retry` are generalized to accept a `FlowPreset` parameter (or derive `FlowSemantics` internally) instead of hardcoding standard-flow stage IDs. All existing hardcoded references to `StageId::Planning`, `StageId::Implementation`, `StageId::PromptReview` in the orchestration loop are replaced with lookups against `FlowSemantics`.\n- [ ] The public engine API is renamed from `execute_standard_run` → `execute_run` and `resume_standard_run` → `resume_run` (keeping the old names as thin wrappers or removing them). The `_with_retry` variants follow the same rename.\n- [ ] `standard_stage_plan()` is generalized to `stage_plan_for_flow(preset: FlowPreset, prompt_review_enabled: bool) -> Vec<StageId>` that derives the executable stage sequence for any preset. For `docs_change` and `ci_improvement`, `prompt_review_enabled` has no effect (no prompt review stage exists). For `standard`, behavior is unchanged.\n- [ ] `standard_stage_plan_for_resume()` is generalized to `stage_plan_for_resume(preset: FlowPreset, events: &[JournalEvent], config: &EffectiveConfig)` with the same journal-reconstruction logic but using flow-specific stage definitions.\n- [ ] `is_remediation_stage()` and `is_late_stage()` are replaced by lookups against `FlowSemantics::remediation_trigger_stages` and `FlowSemantics::late_stages` respectively.\n- [ ] `record_cycle_advance()` uses `FlowSemantics::execution_stage` instead of hardcoded `StageId::Implementation`.\n- [ ] Amendment drain logic (currently keyed to `stage_id == StageId::Planning`) uses `FlowSemantics::planning_stage`.\n- [ ] Completion-round restart (currently targets `StageId::Planning`) uses `FlowSemantics::planning_stage`.\n- [ ] Remediation-cycle restart (currently targets `StageId::Implementation`) uses `FlowSemantics::execution_stage`.\n- [ ] Prompt-review pause check uses `FlowSemantics::prompt_review_stage` (skipped for flows without prompt review).\n- [ ] `docs_change` happy path: `run start` on a docs_change project executes `docs_plan → docs_update → docs_validation → review` in sequence, persisting payload + artifact + journal events at each stage boundary, completing with `RunStatus::Completed`.\n- [ ] `ci_improvement` happy path: `run start` on a ci_improvement project executes `ci_plan → ci_update → ci_validation → review` in sequence with the same persistence guarantees.\n- [ ] `docs_change` remediation: when `docs_validation` or `review` returns `RequestChanges`, the engine triggers a remediation cycle restarting from `docs_update` (not `implementation`), with `CycleAdvanced` journal event emitted.\n- [ ] `ci_improvement` remediation: when `ci_validation` or `review` returns `RequestChanges`, the engine triggers a remediation cycle restarting from `ci_update`.\n- [ ] `docs_change` and `ci_improvement` have no late stages: `ConditionallyApproved` from `docs_validation`, `ci_validation`, or `review` does not trigger completion-round advancement; it is treated as non-late-stage conditional approval (amendments accumulated in snapshot but no completion-round loop).\n- [ ] `Rejected` from any validation stage in docs_change/ci_improvement terminates the run with `QaReviewOutcomeFailure`, same as standard flow.\n- [ ] `run resume` works for `docs_change` and `ci_improvement` projects that are in `Failed` or `Paused` status, reconstructing resume state from journal using flow-specific stage definitions.\n- [ ] Retry semantics (transport failure, schema validation, timeout, cancellation) apply identically to docs_change/ci_improvement stages as they do to standard stages — no flow-specific retry policy changes.\n- [ ] The CLI `run start` and `run resume` handlers in `src/cli/run.rs` remove the `UnsupportedFlow` guard for `DocsChange` and `CiImprovement` (but keep it for `QuickDev` which is deferred to a later loop). They pass the project's `FlowPreset` to the generalized engine.\n- [ ] Completion guard still runs for docs