Resume scenarios for non-standard flows\n- `tests/unit/workflow_engine_test.rs` — New unit tests for generalized engine with docs_change/ci_improvement presets; tests for `FlowSemantics` derivation\n- `tests/unit/flow_semantics_test.rs` — Dedicated unit tests for `FlowSemantics` struct and `flow_semantics()` function\n\n## Dependencies\n- Requires: Loop 8 (Completion Rounds, Late-Stage Acceptance, and Durable Amendments) — the engine must have completion-round and amendment infrastructure in place before generalizing\n- Blocks: Loop 10 (Requirements drafting and project-seed handoff), Loop 11 (Daemon routing which needs all flow presets executable)\n\n---\n\nFILE /root/new-ralph-burning/.ralph/projects/ralph-burning-rewrite/loops/010-requirements-drafting-and-project-seed-handoff/20260312193814-spec.md\n---\nartifact: spec\nloop: 10\nproject: ralph-burning-rewrite\nbackend: codex(gpt-5.4-xhigh)\nrole: planner\ncreated_at: 2026-03-12T19:38:14Z\n---\n\nI’m reviewing the current rewrite workspace, loop artifacts, and git history to determine what is already implemented and what the next missing slice should be. First I’ll inspect `prompt.md`, the completed loop specs, and the current code/test surface so the next feature is grounded in what actually exists.\nThe workspace is the rewrite repo under `ralph-burning-rewrite/`; loop 9 is the latest completed checkpoint. I didn’t get `prompt.md` from the first pass, so I’m narrowing into the rewrite project and the loop/spec artifacts that define current scope and completed behavior.\nI’ve confirmed the planning state lives under `.ralph/projects/ralph-burning-rewrite/`, with loop specs through 009 approved. Next I’m checking the actual prompt, the latest spec, and the code/test surface for `quick_dev`, `requirements`, `daemon`, and `conformance` so I can avoid proposing a slice that is already in place.\nThe shared engine is already generalized for all flow semantics, including `quick_dev`; the only hard block I’ve found there is the CLI guard that still rejects `quick_dev`. In contrast, `requirements`, `daemon`, and `conformance` are still command stubs with empty context modules, so I’m checking whether the roadmap and existing tests make `quick_dev` or `requirements drafting` the next real gap.\nThe roadmap pattern is consistent: loops 1 through 9 map directly to roadmap items 1 through 9, and there’s no loop 10 implementation in git history. I’m pulling the legacy PRD/reference materials now so the next spec can be detailed without accidentally inheriting old storage or protocol decisions.\nI found one architectural coupling that matters for the next slice: `agent_execution` currently hardcodes `workflow_composition::StageContract` and the project-flow `StageId`. Requirements drafting will need structured contracts too, so the spec needs to generalize that interface instead of smuggling requirements stages into the project workflow enum.\n# Feature: Requirements Drafting and Project Seed Handoff\n\n## Description\nLoops 1 through 9 already delivered the rewrite foundation: workspace init and flow discovery, stage contracts and renderers, effective config and active project resolution, canonical project/run storage and queries, agent execution, standard-flow orchestration, retry/resume semantics, completion rounds and amendments, and docs/CI flow execution. Git checkpoint history stops at loop 9 planning, and the entire `requirements` bounded context plus all four `requirements` CLI commands are still stubs at `HEAD`. The next missing roadmap slice is a canonical requirements-run workflow under `.ralph-burning/requirements/` that can draft requirements from an idea, pause for clarifying answers when needed, and emit a durable project-seed handoff without auto-creating a project or touching legacy `.ralph` PRD state.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Introduce a `RequirementsRun` state model persisted at `.ralph-burning/requirements/<run-id>/run.json` with, at minimum, `run_id`, `idea`, `mode` (`draft` or `quick`), `status` (`drafting`, `awaiting_answers`, `completed`, `failed`), `question_round`, `latest_question_set_id`, `latest_draft_id`, `latest_review_id`, `latest_seed_id`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, and `status_summary`.\n- [ ] Each requirements run also persists `journal.ndjson`, `answers.toml`, `answers.json`, `history/payloads/*`, `history/artifacts/*`, `seed/project.json`, `seed/prompt.md`, and `runtime/{logs,backend}/*` under `.ralph-burning/requirements/<run-id>/`.\n- [ ] `requirements show <run-id>` derives its read model from `run.json` and `journal.ndjson`, not by scanning artifacts, and prints the run ID, mode, status, question round, last failure summary if present, pending question count, recommended flow, and the seed prompt path when complete.\n- [ ] Define structured contracts and deterministic renderers for four requirements-stage outputs: `question_set`, `requirements_draft`, `requirements_review`, and `project_seed`.\n- [ ] Requirements contract validation follows the same invariant as project stages: schema validation occurs before any state mutation, domain validation occurs after schema validation and before transition commit, and rendered Markdown is never parsed for control flow.\n- [ ] `question_set` payloads include stable question IDs, prompt text, rationale, `required` flag, and optional suggested defaults; those IDs are the only keys accepted in `answers.toml` and persisted `answers.json`.\n- [ ] `requirements_draft` payloads include a problem summary, goals, non-goals, constraints, acceptance criteria, risks or open questions, and a recommended flow constrained to the built-in presets only: `standard`, `quick_dev`, `docs_change`, or `ci_improvement`.\n- [ ] `project_seed` payloads include a recommended project `id`, project `name`, built-in `flow`, a final `prompt.md` body, and a short handoff summary suitable for manual `project create --prompt`.\n- [ ] `requirements draft --idea \"<text>\"` creates a new run, durably records the idea, invokes question generation, and either transitions to `awaiting_answers` after committing the question payload/artifact plus an editable `answers.toml` template, or continues directly into draft/review/seed generation when no questions are required.\n- [ ] `requirements quick --idea \"<text>\"` creates a new run in `quick` mode, skips question generation entirely, and executes draft -> review -> seed generation in one command using the same persistence and validation rules.\n- [ ] `requirements answer <run-id>` is valid for runs in `awaiting_answers` and for failed runs whose latest durable boundary is a committed question set; it opens `<run-dir>/answers.toml` in `$EDITOR`, validates that every required question has a non-empty answer, persists `answers.json`, and resumes from the answers boundary instead of creating a new run.\n- [ ] If `$EDITOR` fails or exits non-zero during `requirements answer`, the run state, journal, and previously accepted answers remain unchanged.\n- [ ] Requirements drafting reuses `agent_execution`, but `agent_execution` must be generalized from workflow-only `StageContract` usage to a domain-neutral structured-contract interface so requirements contracts do not have to be added to the project workflow `StageId` enum.\n- [ ] Planner defaults drive question generation, drafting, and project-seed generation; reviewer defaults drive requirements review; existing workspace default backend/model resolution and raw-output persistence rules continue to apply.\n- [ ] Review outcomes have distinct semantics: `approved` allows seed generation and completion; `conditionally_approved` still completes but records follow-ups in canonical seed metadata and the rendered handoff summary; `request_changes` and `rejected` fail the run after the review payload/artifact are durably committed and before any seed files become visible.\n- [ ] State invariants for partial failure are explicit: if the question payload/artifact pair fails to persist, the run must not transition to `awaiting_answers` and no partial question/template files may remain visible.\n- [ ] State invariants for partial failure are explicit: if answer validation fails, `answers.json` is not replaced, no draft/review/seed stage runs, and the run remains at the same committed question boundary.\n- [ ] State invariants for partial failure are explicit: if the draft or review payload/artifact pair fails to persist, the corresponding journal success event is not appended and no downstream stage begins.\n- [ ] State invariants for partial failure are explicit: if `seed/project.json` is written but `seed/prompt.md` fails, both seed outputs are removed, the run remains non-completed, and only the already committed draft/review history survives.\n- [ ] Completed requirements runs are immutable, failed runs retain the latest committed question set, answers, draft, and review artifacts, and `question_round` is monotonic across repeated answer cycles.\n- [ ] `requirements show <run-id>` prints a suggested `ralph-burning project create --id ... --name ... --flow ... --prompt <seed/prompt.md>` command assembled from `seed/project.json` and `seed/prompt.md`.\n- [ ] This loop does not auto-create, mutate, select, or delete projects; project handoff is durable seed output only, leaving `project create` as an explicit user action.\n- [ ] Public behavior is covered by new Gherkin scenarios for: draft requiring answers, draft with no questions, quick-mode happy path, editor failure, answer validation failure, conditional approval handoff, review request_changes failure, and seed-write rollback.\n- [ ] Existing workspace, project, and run behavior remains unchanged, including the current quick_dev run-execution deferral outside the `requirements` command surface.\n\n## Files to Modify/Create\n- `src/contexts/requirements_drafting/mod.rs` - replace the placeholder with module exports and public entrypoints for the requirements lifecycle\n- `src/contexts/requirements_drafting/model.rs` - add requirements run IDs, status enums, journal event types, pointers to latest payloads, and seed metadata\n- `src/contexts/requirements_drafting/contracts.rs` - define domain-neutral contracts for `question_set`, `requirements_draft`, `requirements_review`, and `project_seed`\n- `src/contexts/requirements_drafting/renderers.rs` - render deterministic `questions.md`, `requirements.md`, `review.md`, and seed handoff artifacts\n- `src/contexts/requirements_drafting/service.rs` - orchestrate `draft`, `quick`, `show`, and `answer`, including answer-template validation and seed rollback rules\n- `src/contexts/agent_execution/model.rs` - generalize invocation metadata away from workflow-only `StageContract` coupling\n- `src/contexts/agent_execution/service.rs` - support domain-neutral contract evaluation while preserving existing workflow behavior\n- `src/contexts/workflow_composition/contracts.rs` - adapt existing workflow stage contracts to the generalized agent-execution contract interface\n- `src/adapters/fs.rs` - add filesystem stores for requirements runs, journals, answer files, payload/artifact history, runtime diagnostics, and atomic seed-pair writes\n- `src/adapters/stub_backend.rs` - add deterministic requirements-stage payloads for tests\n- `src/cli/requirements.rs` - implement all four requirements commands and the editor-driven answer flow\n- `src/shared/error.rs` - add invalid requirements state, answer validation, and seed persistence error variants\n- `tests/conformance/features/requirements_drafting.feature` - add public requirements-drafting scenarios\n- `tests/unit/requirements_drafting_test.rs` - add domain and service tests for the requirements state machine and failure invariants\n- `tests/cli.rs` - add end-to-end CLI coverage for `requirements draft`, `requirements quick`, `requirements show`, and `requirements answer`\n\n## Dependencies\n- Requires: Loop 9 (Docs Change and CI Improvement Flow Execution)\n- Blocks: Loop 11 (Daemon routing, tasks, leases, watchers, rebase, and interactive requirements path)\n\n---\n\nFILE /root/new-ralph-burning/.ralph/projects/ralph-burning-rewrite/loops/011-daemon-routing-tasks-leases-and-worktree/20260312223344-spec.md\n---\nartifact: spec\nloop: 11\nproject: ralph-burning-rewrite\nbackend: claude(opus)\nrole: planner\ncreated_at: 2026-03-12T22:33:44Z\n---\n\nI now have a complete picture of the codebase state and what's needed. Let me write the spec for Loop 11.\n\n# Feature: Daemon Routing, Tasks, Leases, and Worktree Management\n\n## Description\nImplement the `automation_runtime` bounded context and daemon CLI commands, delivering the full daemon task lifecycle: routing resolution (command > label > repo default), durable task and lease persistence, git worktree isolation per task, reconciliation of orphaned state, and integration with the existing workflow engine for automated project execution. This covers delivery roadmap item #11: \"Daemon routing, tasks, leases, watchers, rebase, interactive requirements path.\"\n\nThe daemon is a long-running foreground process that polls for task files, acquires worktree leases, dispatches work through the generalized `execute_run` / `resume_run` engine, and cleans up on completion. Tasks are created externally (by future GitHub watchers or manually) and placed in `daemon/tasks/`. The daemon picks up pending tasks, enforces invariants (one task per issue, one writer per project, one worktree per lease), and drives them to completion or failure.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `DaemonTask` model with lifecycle states: `pending`, `claimed`, `active`, `completed`, `failed`, `aborted` — persisted as JSON under `.ralph-burning/daemon/tasks/<task-id>.json`\n- [ ] `WorktreeLease` model with fields: lease ID, task ID, worktree path, branch name, acquired-at timestamp, TTL, heartbeat timestamp — persisted under `.ralph-burning/daemon/leases/<lease-id>.json`\n- [ ] **Routing engine** resolves flow preset from task metadata using strict precedence: (1) explicit `routing_command` field → (2) `routing_labels` array → (3) workspace `default_flow` config. Command and label values validated against built-in presets only; unknown values produce `RoutingResolutionFailed` error.\n- [ ] **Label parser** accepts `rb:flow:<preset>` format (e.g., `rb:flow:standard`, `rb:flow:quick_dev`, `rb:flow:docs_change`, `rb:flow:ci_improvement`). Malformed labels are ignored with a warning; conflicting flow labels produce `AmbiguousRouting` error.\n- [ ] **Task creation** via `DaemonTaskService::create_task()` validates: no existing active task for the same `issue_ref`, routing resolves to a valid flow preset, and the task file is atomically written.\n- [ ] **Task claim** acquires a writer lock for the target project (advisory file lock under `daemon/leases/`), creates a worktree lease, and transitions task to `claimed`. If the writer lock is held, the task stays `pending` and is retried on next poll.\n- [ ] **Worktree lifecycle**: on claim, create a git worktree at a deterministic path (`.ralph-burning/worktrees/<task-id>/`); on task terminal state, remove the worktree and release the lease. Worktree creation failure transitions task to `failed` with explicit error.\n- [ ] **Task dispatch**: once claimed, the daemon creates a project (if needed) and invokes `execute_run` or `resume_run` from the workflow engine within the worktree context. The task transitions to `active` during execution and to `completed` or `failed` based on run outcome.\n- [ ] **Heartbeat**: active tasks update `WorktreeLease.last_heartbeat` periodically. Reconciliation uses heartbeat staleness to detect orphaned leases.\n- [ ] **Invariant: one writer lock per project** — enforced by advisory lease file; attempting to claim a second task for the same project while a lease is held returns `ProjectWriterLockHeld`.\n- [ ] **Invariant: one active daemon task per issue** — enforced at task creation; `create_task` with a duplicate `issue_ref` where existing task is non-terminal returns `DuplicateTaskForIssue`.\n- [ ] **Invariant: one worktree lease per task** — enforced at claim; a task that already has a lease cannot acquire another.\n- [ ] **`daemon start`** CLI: runs the daemon event loop. Polls `daemon/tasks/` for `pending` tasks at a configurable interval (default 10s). Processes one task at a time per poll cycle. Logs task lifecycle transitions. Exits cleanly on SIGINT/SIGTERM with lease cleanup.\n- [ ] **`daemon status`** CLI: lists all tasks with their current state, associated lease (if any), and last heartbeat. Non-terminal tasks shown first.\n- [ ] **`daemon abort <task-id>`** CLI: transitions a `claimed` or `active` task to `aborted`, cancels any in-progress backend invocation (via existing `CancellationToken`), releases the worktree lease, and removes the worktree. Aborting a terminal task returns an error.\n- [ ] **`daemon retry <task-id>`** CLI: transitions a `failed` task back to `pending` (incrementing attempt count). Retrying a non-failed task returns an error.\n- [ ] **`daemon reconcile`** CLI: scans leases for stale heartbeats (configurable TTL, default 5 minutes), removes orphaned worktrees, releases stale leases, and transitions any `claimed`/`active` tasks with stale leases to `failed` with `reconciliation_timeout` failure class. Reports actions taken.\n- [ ] **Rebase support**: before dispatching a claimed task, the daemon attempts `git rebase` of the worktree branch onto the upstream default branch. If rebase fails (conflicts), the task transitions to `failed` with `rebase_conflict` details rather than silently proceeding with a stale base.\n- [ ] **Journal integration**: daemon lifecycle events (task_created, task_claimed, task_completed, task_failed, task_aborted, lease_acquired, lease_released, reconciliation_run) are appended to a daemon-level journal at `.ralph-burning/daemon/journal.ndjson`.\n- [ ] **Error variants** added to `AppError`: `RoutingResolutionFailed`, `AmbiguousRouting`, `DuplicateTaskForIssue`, `ProjectWriterLockHeld`, `WorktreeCreationFailed`, `WorktreeRemovalFailed`, `LeaseStale`, `TaskStateTransitionInvalid`, `RebaseConflict`.\n- [ ] **Conformance scenarios** in `tests/conformance/features/daemon_routing.feature` covering: routing precedence (command > label > default), label parsing valid/invalid, conflicting labels, task lifecycle state machine, lease acquisition/release, duplicate task rejection, abort/retry semantics, reconciliation of stale leases.\n- [ ] **Unit tests** for: routing resolution logic, label parser, task state machine transitions, lease TTL calculations, worktree path derivation.\n- [ ] All existing tests continue to pass (272+ tests).\n\n## Files to Modify/Create\n- `src/contexts/automation_runtime/mod.rs` — Module declarations, re-exports, `CONTEXT_NAME`\n- `src/contexts/automation_runtime/model.rs` — `DaemonTask`, `TaskStatus`, `WorktreeLease`, `RoutingSource`, `RoutingResolution`, `DaemonJournalEvent`, `DaemonJournalEventType` types\n- `src/contexts/automation_runtime/routing.rs` — `RoutingEngine` with `resolve_flow()`, label parser, command parser, precedence logic\n- `src/contexts/automation_runtime/task_service.rs` — `DaemonTaskService` with create/claim/dispatch/complete/fail/abort/retry operations and invariant enforcement\n- `src/contexts/automation_runtime/lease_service.rs` — `LeaseService` with acquire/release/heartbeat/reconcile operations\n- `src/contexts/automation_runtime/daemon_loop.rs` — `DaemonLoop` event loop: poll, claim, rebase, dispatch, cleanup\n- `src/adapters/worktree.rs` — `WorktreeAdapter` for git worktree create/remove/rebase operations (shells out to `git` CLI)\n- `src/adapters/fs.rs` — Add `FsDaemonStore` implementing task/lease/journal persistence under `daemon/`\n- `src/adapters/mod.rs` — Register `worktree` module\n- `src/cli/daemon.rs` — Implement all five subcommand handlers replacing `NotYetImplemented` stubs\n- `src/shared/error.rs` — Add daemon-specific error variants\n- `src/contexts/project_run_record/model.rs` — Add `DaemonJournalEventType` variants to support daemon journal events (or keep separate journal type)\n- `tests/conformance/features/daemon_routing.feature` — Gherkin scenarios for routing, tasks, leases, reconciliation\n- `tests/conformance/features/daemon_lifecycle.feature` — Gherkin scenarios for start/abort/retry/status flows\n- `tests/unit/automation_runtime_test.rs` — Unit tests for routing, task state machine, lease logic\n\n## Dependencies\n- Requires: Loop 10 (requirements drafting — for interactive requirements path integration), Loop 9 (generalized workflow engine — for `execute_run`/`resume_run` dispatch), Loop 7 (retry/failure semantics — task failure classification reuses `FailureClass`)\n- Blocks: Loop 12 (Cutover — conformance gate in CI, no legacy runtime paths)\n\n---\n\nFILE /root/new-ralph-burning/.ralph/projects/ralph-burning-rewrite/loops/012-quick-dev-flow-public-execution/20260312232520-spec.md\n---\nartifact: spec\nloop: 12\nproject: ralph-burning-rewrite\nbackend: codex(gpt-5.4-xhigh)\nrole: planner\ncreated_at: 2026-03-12T23:25:20Z\n---\n\nI’m checking the rewrite workspace against the roadmap, completed loop specs, and git history to identify the next missing slice rather than re-planning finished work. First I’ll inspect `prompt.md`, the loop artifacts, and recent commits, then I’ll map what’s already implemented in code versus what remains from the master prompt.\nI’ve confirmed loop 11 is the last completed checkpoint in git, so I’m narrowing on what roadmap item is still unimplemented after daemon routing/worktree management. Next I’m reading the current planning artifacts and the rewrite source tree without `target/` noise to see whether the remaining gap is quick-dev flow support, daemon watcher/rebase behavior, or the final cutover/conformance CI slice.\nThe repo already contains conformance and daemon code, but the file list alone isn’t enough because some roadmap items are only partially covered. I’m reading the current project prompt, loop 11 spec, and the flow/runtime tests to confirm which remaining behavior is actually absent from the rewrite.\nOne clear gap is the conformance CLI: `conformance list/run` is still a stub even though the Gherkin files exist. I’m checking whether anything earlier in the roadmap is also still missing, especially the `quick_dev` preset and the rest of the roadmap item 11 scope, so the next feature I pick is genuinely the highest-priority unimplemented slice.\nI found a second substantial gap: `quick_dev` exists in flow discovery and stage contracts, but the runtime deliberately rejects it. That means the project is not complete, and I need to compare whether `quick_dev` execution should come before the conformance runner or whether the remaining roadmap prioritizes the conformance/CI cutover first.\nRequirements drafting is in place, so the remaining gap is not loop 10. I’m now isolating whether loop 11 is still incomplete because there is no watcher/interactive requirements bridge, or whether the next real slice is loop 12: a real conformance runner plus CI gate and final cutover cleanup.\nThe remaining picture is clearer now: requirements is implemented, daemon routing/worktrees are implemented, but there is still no CI workflow in the repo and the conformance command is an explicit stub. I’m checking the engine internals one more time to see whether `quick_dev` is a real missing product feature or just deferred by policy, because that determines whether the next spec should target `quick_dev` or the conformance/CI cutover.\nI found an important inconsistency: `run start`/`run resume` explicitly reject `quick_dev`, but the generalized workflow engine and daemon routing already know about `quick_dev` stages and semantics. That makes `quick_dev` enablement a better next slice than CI cutover, because cutover would still leave one built-in flow preset unusable from the public CLI.\nI found another explicit gap in the public CLI contract: `run rollback` still returns `NotYetImplemented`. I’m checking whether rollback has any supporting domain/storage implementation already in place, because if it’s mostly absent it may outrank `quick_dev` as the next slice.\n# Feature: Quick Dev Flow Public Execution\n\n## Description\nLoops 1 through 11 already delivered the rewrite foundation: workspace/bootstrap, flow discovery, stage contracts/renderers, effective config, canonical project/run storage, agent execution, standard/docs/CI orchestration, retry/resume/failure semantics, completion rounds/amendments, requirements drafting, and daemon routing/tasks/worktrees. The remaining core workflow gap is `quick_dev`: the preset, stages, contracts, renderer support, requirements recommendations, and daemon routing already exist, but `run start` and `run resume` still hard-fail with `UnsupportedFlow`, and current conformance/CLI coverage still encodes that deferral.\n\nThe next logical feature is to remove that public deferral and make `quick_dev` a first-class executable preset before planning the conformance/CI cutover. That keeps the scope focused on the missing behavior only, rather than re-planning engine generalization, daemon routing, or requirements work that is already complete.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `ralph-burning run start` accepts projects with flow `quick_dev`; the explicit `UnsupportedFlow` rejection path is removed for `quick_dev` while all existing run-state precondition checks remain unchanged.\n- [ ] `ralph-burning run resume` accepts failed `quick_dev` runs from durable stage boundaries; resume must continue from canonical run snapshot + journal state, never from artifact scans or Markdown parsing.\n- [ ] `quick_dev` executes the canonical stage order `plan_and_implement -> review -> apply_fixes -> final_review`; `prompt_review.enabled` has no effect on this stage plan and no prompt-review pause path is introduced.\n- [ ] Happy-path `quick_dev` execution persists exactly one payload record and one rendered artifact per stage, appends the expected `run_started`, `stage_entered`, `stage_completed`, and `run_completed` journal events in sequence order, and finishes with `run.json` in `completed` status, no active run, and `completion_rounds = 1`.\n- [ ] Preflight for `quick_dev` validates all four stages before any state mutation. If capability or availability checks fail for any `quick_dev` stage, `run.json`, `journal.ndjson`, payload history, artifact history, and sessions remain unchanged.\n- [ ] On `review = approved` or `conditionally_approved`, the run continues to `apply_fixes` in the same cycle with the persisted review payload/artifact preserved in durable history.\n- [ ] On `review = request_changes`, the non-passing review payload/artifact must still be durably committed before transition; then the engine emits `cycle_advanced`, increments the cycle monotonically, and restarts at `apply_fixes`. If `cycle_advanced` persistence fails, the run becomes failed and no partially-advanced cursor is committed.\n- [ ] On `review = rejected`, the review payload/artifact remain durable history, the run transitions to `failed`, and no remediation-cycle advance occurs.\n- [ ] On `final_review = approved`, the run completes normally. On `final_review = conditionally_approved` or `request_changes`, the final-review payload/artifact are committed first, durable amendments are queued, `completion_round_advanced` is appended, and the run restarts at `plan_and_implement` for the next completion round; cycle and completion-round counters remain monotonic and independent.\n- [ ] Failure invariant for late-stage amendment persistence: if any amendment file in the `quick_dev` final-review batch fails to persist, any already-written files from that batch are removed, `run.json` amendment queue remains unchanged, and no completion-round advancement is recorded.\n- [ ] `run status`, `run history`, and `run tail` correctly expose `quick_dev` stage names, cycle progression, and completion-round progression from canonical state with no special casing that treats the flow as deferred.\n- [ ] A daemon task routed to `quick_dev` completes through the same workflow engine path without surfacing `UnsupportedFlow`, preserving the existing daemon task/lease invariants from loop 11.\n- [ ] Conformance and CLI coverage are updated so `quick_dev` is tested as supported behavior, replacing the current “quick_dev remains deferred” assertions. Coverage must include: happy path, review remediation, final-review completion-round restart, failed-run resume, and preflight-no-mutation semantics.\n- [ ] Existing `standard`, `docs_change`, `ci_improvement`, requirements-drafting, and daemon-routing behavior remains unchanged except for the removal of the `quick_dev` deferral.\n\n## Files to Modify/Create\n- `src/cli/run.rs` - remove the `quick_dev` guard in `run start`/`run resume` and preserve the existing canonical-state validation flow.\n- `src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs` - tighten any `quick_dev` transition/resume edge cases revealed by new coverage, especially review remediation and final-review completion-round restart behavior.\n- `src/shared/error.rs` - remove or repurpose the now-stale `UnsupportedFlow` path for `quick_dev`.\n- `tests/conformance/features/run_start_quick_dev.feature` - add public `quick_dev` scenarios for start, remediation, final-review restart, and preflight failure invariants.\n- `tests/conformance/features/run_resume_non_standard.feature` - extend resume coverage to include `quick_dev` durable-boundary recovery.\n- `tests/conformance/features/run_start_standard.feature` - delete or replace the existing assertions that `quick_dev` is deferred.\n- `tests/unit/workflow_engine_test.rs` - add engine-level `quick_dev` lifecycle, failure, and resume tests.\n- `tests/unit/flow_semantics_test.rs` - add `quick_dev` stage-plan and prompt-review-ignorance regression coverage.\n- `tests/cli.rs` - convert the current `quick_dev` rejection tests into success-path and resume-path CLI coverage, plus one routed-daemon regression case.\n\n## Dependencies\n- Requires: Loop 7 (retry/resume/failure semantics), Loop 8 (completion rounds and durable amendments), Loop 9 (shared flow engine for non-standard presets)\n- Blocks: Conformance runner and CI cutover, overall v1 flow-preset completeness\n\n---\n\nFILE /root/new-ralph-burning/.ralph/projects/ralph-burning-rewrite/loops/013-run-rollback/20260312234518-spec.md\n---\nartifact: spec\nloop: 13\nproject: ralph-burning-rewrite\nbackend: claude(opus)\nrole: planner\ncreated_at: 2026-03-12T23:45:18Z\n---\n\nNow I have the full picture. Here's the analysis:\n\n**Completed (Loops 3-12):** Roadmap items 1-11 are done. All four flow presets execute end-to-end. Requirements drafting, daemon routing, retry/resume, completion rounds, and amendments are all implemented.\n\n**Remaining gaps:**\n1. **`run rollback`** — CLI stub returns `NotYetImplemented`; `RollbackPoint` model exists but is never created/persisted; no rollback service logic; no Gherkin feature file\n2. **`conformance list/run`** — CLI returns `NotYetImplemented`; `conformance_spec` context is a placeholder; 17 Gherkin feature files exist but no runner harness\n3. Roadmap item 12 (cutover) — depends on conformance gate\n\nThe next logical feature is **Run Rollback**, as it's a core invariant requirement and a prerequisite for cutover completeness.\n\n# Feature: Run Rollback\n\n## Description\nImplement the `ralph-burning run rollback --to <target> [--hard]` command, which allows a user to rewind a project's run state to a previously-completed durable stage boundary. A *logical* (soft) rollback resets the stage cursor and run snapshot to the rollback point without touching the repository working tree. A *hard* rollback additionally performs a repository reset (via the worktree adapter) to the git state recorded at the rollback point. The core invariant \"logical rollback must happen before repository reset\" governs the ordering for hard rollback. Rollback points are created automatically at each durable stage boundary during run execution and persisted under `projects/<project-id>/rollback/`. The feature also adds automatic rollback-point creation to the workflow engine's stage-completion path so that every successful stage transition produces a recoverable checkpoint.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] The workflow engine creates a `RollbackPoint` after every successful stage completion and persists it under `projects/<project-id>/rollback/<rollback-id>.json` via the filesystem adapter.\n- [ ] Each rollback point captures the rollback ID (UUID), timestamp, completed stage ID, cycle number, and a snapshot of the run state at that boundary.\n- [ ] `run rollback --to <stage>` (soft/logical) validates that the target stage has a persisted rollback point for the active project, resets `run.json` to the captured snapshot, appends a `rollback_performed` journal event, updates `rollback_point_meta` (increments `rollback_count`, sets `last_rollback_id`), and sets run status to `paused` so the user must explicitly `run resume` to continue.\n- [ ] `run rollback --to <stage> --hard` performs the logical rollback first, then invokes the worktree adapter to reset the repository to the git commit SHA recorded in the rollback point. If the git reset fails, the logical rollback is still durable (invariant: logical before physical).\n- [ ] Rollback is only allowed when the run is in `failed` or `paused` status. Attempting rollback on `running`, `not_started`, or `completed` runs fails with an explicit error message.\n- [ ] The `--to` target must name a stage that belongs to the project's flow preset; specifying an invalid stage name or a stage with no rollback point fails with a descriptive error.\n- [ ] Rollback to a stage discards payload and artifact records for all stages after the target (they remain on disk but are excluded from `run history` and `run status` queries by the journal's rollback event acting as a logical boundary).\n- [ ] `run history` and `run status` correctly reflect post-rollback state, showing the rollback event and only pre-rollback-point history.\n- [ ] Hard rollback records the git commit SHA in the rollback point; the `RollbackPoint` model gains an optional `git_sha: Option<String>` field populated by the engine when a stage completes.\n- [ ] Rollback count and last rollback ID are monotonic across multiple rollbacks within the same run.\n- [ ] A new Gherkin feature file `tests/conformance/features/run_rollback.feature` defines at least 8 scenarios covering: soft rollback success, hard rollback success, rollback from wrong status, rollback to invalid stage, rollback to stage without checkpoint, multiple sequential rollbacks, rollback then resume continues from target, and hard rollback with git-reset failure preserving logical state.\n- [ ] Unit tests cover rollback domain validation (status check, stage membership, rollback-point lookup) and snapshot restoration logic.\n- [ ] Adapter contract tests verify rollback-point persistence round-trip (write, list, read by stage).\n\n## Files to Modify/Create\n- `src/contexts/project_run_record/model.rs` — Add `git_sha: Option<String>` to `RollbackPoint`; add `RollbackPerformed` variant to journal event enum.\n- `src/contexts/project_run_record/service.rs` — Add rollback service functions: `perform_rollback()`, `list_rollback_points()`, `get_rollback_point_for_stage()`. Add `RollbackPointStorePort` trait for adapter boundary.\n- `src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs` — After each successful stage completion, create and persist a `RollbackPoint` capturing current run state and optional git SHA. Wire through the `RollbackPointStorePort`.\n- `src/adapters/fs.rs` — Implement `RollbackPointStorePort`: write rollback points as JSON under `rollback/`, list rollback points, read by stage ID.\n- `src/cli/run.rs` — Replace `NotYetImplemented` for `Rollback` variant with actual handler calling rollback service. Parse `--to` as a `StageId`, resolve project, load rollback point, delegate to service.\n- `src/shared/error.rs` — Add rollback-specific error variants: `RollbackPointNotFound`, `RollbackInvalidStatus`, `RollbackStageNotInFlow`, `RollbackGitResetFailed`.\n- `src/adapters/worktree.rs` — Add `reset_to_sha()` method (or equivalent) for hard rollback git operations.\n- `tests/conformance/features/run_rollback.feature` — New Gherkin feature file with scenarios per acceptance criteria.\n- `tests/unit/rollback_test.rs` — Domain-level unit tests for rollback validation and state restoration.\n- `tests/unit/adapter_contract_test.rs` — Extend with rollback-point persistence round-trip tests.\n\n## Dependencies\n- Requires: Loop 7 (Retry, Remediation, Resume — provides `RunStatus`, `RollbackPointMeta` model, and resume semantics that rollback interacts with), Loop 4 (Project/Run Record — provides run snapshot and journal infrastructure)\n- Blocks: Roadmap item 12 (Cutover / Conformance Gate — rollback is the last missing runtime command before the CLI surface is complete)\n\n---\n\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
